text:
Normally I wouldn't write a comment, but I need to try and make a bit of advice that would be incredibly useful to anyone at Guras skill level, considering she is new to fighting games.
So instead of making the original comment I was going to do initially about some minor tips regarding basic movement, there is one take that is so much more important for her to know.

Combos are NOT the end all be all.
This is something that must be stated, as people surrounding Fighting games, (that aren't super into them), have this weird obsession with thinking you need to know how to do combos to be good.
This is false, if you know how to move around well, understand your moves, what moves that can kill, which moves deal damage, which moves are fast, shielding, dodging, etc... you do not need combos.
In fact, if you don't know how to do the basic things, combos are absolutely useless knowledge.
Combos are for "advanced" players to easily get more damage from getting a single hit.
If you don't know combos, that just means you have to land more hits, which isn't a problem, unless you don't get the basic functions, to which it should be again obvious, learning combos is even more useless, as you should probably learn basic moves first.

Just wanted to make that clarification before anything else.
Combos are not important.
yes, there is a point where they are nice to have, and they are cool.

But Combos are STILL NOT important, YET!
Combos are never among the first thing you should worry about.

text:
Gura didn't see my superchat during the stream, so a few helpful beginner tips for our upcoming smash-shark. hopefully Gura sees these.

1) you can jump using the X or Y buttons. this makes it easier to control yourself in air, rather than using up on the left thumbstick

2) you can use the right thumbstick (or c-stick if using a gamecube controller) to use smash attacks. flicking the stick up uses the up+a, flicking the stick down uses down+a, and flicking the stick to the side uses the left+a or right+a, depending on the direction you flick it. You can also hold the right thumbstick in those directions to charge your smash attack.

3) you have different a-button moves in the air than you do while standing on the ground. Similarly, you can use the right thumbstick to use these moves as well. there are also some more advanced a-button moves, and some special moves depending on the character, but stick with the basics to get a better feel.

4) the R button (or the Z button if using a gamecube controller) is your grab. different characters have different grab ranges, but most of them are melee-range. when you grab a character, you can tap the a-button to get a few hits on them while they are grabbed, before throwing them away. You throw the character in a different direction based off of where you tilt the left thumbstick when you want to end a grab. tilting it up throws them in the air, tilting it down throws them to the ground, and tilting left or right will throw them away from you either in front or behind you, depending on the direction you're facing.
 
 
 
 
these are the tips I think would benefit Gura the most. If anyone has some tips they'd like to add, feel free to post a reply to my comment. I am no smash expert/pro, but I want to see our shark succeed.

text:
To add onto tip 3, a majority of the characters should be played by using mainly air attacks. Or more specifically, around 60%+ of your attacks should be aerials, depending on the character. This is due to the higher mobility granted during the attack, the quickness of said attacks, and the lack of ending lag for most aerial attacks upon landing.
There are certain exception characters that should very obviously not fight in the air, which you can easily tell once you see their aerials. Several characters can also get away with just spamming smash attacks on CPUs(*cough*dorfman*cough*), but can obviously not get away with it against most players.
